DSCI 100 Final Project¶

Edward Huang, Jonathan Lee, Ryan Gao

Introduction¶

There are a variety of factors that can influence an individual's financial situation and their lifestyle. This project aims to predict whether an individual will earn >50k or <=50k a year based on some factors. We are using the Adult Data Set from UCI Machine Learning Repository which contains data on a variety of socioeconomic factors including age, workclass, fnlwgt, education, education_num, marital_status, occupation, relationship, race, sex, capital_gain, capital_loss, hours_per_week, and native_country. We will use some of these factors as predictors in this analysis to predict an invdividual's income. This data is from a census conducted in 1994, and the predictors will be explained in the "Method" section below.

Question: Given a set of predictors pertaining to an individual, will their yearly income be >50k or <=50k?

Methods and Results¶

First, we need to load the appropriate libraries and then transfer the data from the website into R, since the data is hosted on the UCI website. We can do this by using the read_csv function. Since there are currently no titles for any of the columns, we must change this by using the colnames() function. The column names that we are using are found in the attributes section of the "Adult Data Set" website. However, some of them were not clear so we improved upon them.

After column names are applied, the data will be tidy because each variable is in its own column, each observation is in its own row, and each cell has one data point.

sum(is.na(data))

Luckily there were no NAs in the data so no further data tidying is necessary.

Variable Definitions¶

Before we proceed with our preliminary data analysis, we need to understand what each of the columns represents. While some of the variables are self-explanatory, such as age, race, and sex, some of them still need to be clarified.

In this dataset, fnlwgt denotes the final weight, which is a numerical value that is used for scaling purposes in the census.

The variables capital_gain and capital_loss represent the income generated aside from each individuals salary.

Choosing Predictors¶

We exclude all non-numerical variables to keep things simple, because it is difficult to compute the distance between categorical variables. Additionally, capital_gain and capital_loss are not included because they change year to year and are not consistent.

Since the only purpose of the variable fnlwgt is to assign weights to similar demographics and therefore has no predictive capability, we chose to exclude it as well.

So, we are left with four remaining variables: hours_worked_per_week, education_yrs, age, and income.

Additionally, we also must convert the target variable, income into a factor because it is the categorical class that we are predicting for.

In [4]:
data_new <- data %>%
select(hours_worked_per_week, education_yrs, age, income) %>%
mutate(income = as.factor(income))

Figure 1.0 ggpairs Analysis for Possible Predictor Variables

By examining the bottom row of this figure, we can find the correlation between each predictor variable and the target variable. We can see that the centre of the distribution, which is the mean, is shifted to the right for those making over 50K in each of the graphs. This would indicate a positive relationship between income and each of the predictors, as an individuals salary will generally increase if they are older, more educated, and work more during the week.

One thing that is of note is the peak in the hours_work_per_week distribution. The one visible peak appears to be at ~40 hours per week, which makes sense as a 40 hour workweek is the norm. This means that the distribution for hours_worked_per_week is significantly influenced by one data point, so it is not a reliable predictor.

Thus, the predictors we will use for the analysis are age and education_yrs, so we can remove hours_worked_per_week from the data frame.

In [6]:
data_new <- data_new %>%
select(-hours_worked_per_week)

Building the Classifier¶

We need to preprocess the data, specifically centering and scaling predictors. We will do this by creating a recipe.

In [16]:
set.seed(2020) 

income_recipe <- recipe(income ~ education_yrs + age , data = data_train) %>%
   step_scale(all_predictors()) %>%
   step_center(all_predictors())
income_recipe

Data Recipe

Inputs:

      role #variables
   outcome          1
 predictor          2

Operations:

Scaling for all_predictors()
Centering for all_predictors()

We will now find the optimal value of k for the classifier. The first step will be to perform cross-validation on the training data, and we will use 5 folds.

In [17]:
set.seed(2020)

income_vfold <- vfold_cv(data_train, v = 5, strata = income)

Build the tune model, specifying the engine as kknn and mode as classification because we are doing a classification problem. We set neighbors to tune() because we have not chosen k yet.

In [18]:
set.seed(2020) 

knn_tune <- nearest_neighbor(weight_func = "rectangular", neighbors = tune()) %>%
      set_engine("kknn") %>%
      set_mode("classification")
knn_tune

K-Nearest Neighbor Model Specification (classification)

Main Arguments:
  neighbors = tune()
  weight_func = rectangular

Computational engine: kknn

Now, we can run cross-validation across the folds with the tune model made and the recipe made earlier, income_recipe. We use collect_metrics to collect the results of the cross-validation. The cross-validation takes around 2 minute 20 seconds to run on our computer, due to the size of the data set.

In [19]:
set.seed(1234)

knn_results <- workflow() %>%
      add_recipe(income_recipe) %>%
      add_model(knn_tune) %>%
      tune_grid(resamples = income_vfold, grid = 10) %>%
      collect_metrics()

As can be seen from the graph k = 13 seems to be the optimal value of k, meaning it will achieve the highest accuracy in its predictions with that value. We will verify the best value of k by extracting the k value with highest value from Table 1.4.

In [22]:
k_val <- accuracies %>%
    arrange(desc(mean)) %>%
    select(neighbors) %>%
    slice(1) %>%
    pull()
k_val
13

The optimal k value is indeed 13. We will now build our classifier with the best value of k.

In [23]:
set.seed(2020)
income_spec_best <- nearest_neighbor(weight_func = "rectangular", neighbors = k_val) %>%
      set_engine("kknn") %>%
      set_mode("classification")

income_best_fit <- workflow() %>%
      add_recipe(income_recipe) %>%
      add_model(income_spec_best) %>%
      fit(data = data_train)

Discussion¶

Now, we can plot a scatterplot of our predictions to see if any trends are able to be discerned.

In [30]:
predictions_plot <- income_test_best_predictions %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = age, y = education_yrs, colour = .pred_class)) +
    geom_point() +
    ggtitle("Age vs Years of Education (from Predictions)") +
    labs(x = "Age", y = "Years of Education", colour = "Yearly Income")
predictions_plot

Figure 1.7 Results of Predictions based on Training Data

Given data from our predetermined predictors, we expected that our classification model would be able to generate an accurate prediction based on the training data. When comparing the points from Figure 1.6 and Figure 1.7, we see that the positions of the points on the graph are quite similar. In other words, if we were to superimpose the two graphs together, then the points would line up according to colour. The reason that the data points seem to be arranged in rows is due to the fact that age is discrete.

The accuracy of our model was found to be ~78%, which is a good percentage. If the accuracy of our model was considering that we are not predicting for anything high stakes, like in the medical field. If that were the case, we would want the accuracy to be higher.

From Figure 1.7, we see that as the years of education increase, the yearly income of people tends to be >50K. Additionally, we see a downwards "peak" at approximately 50 years old. People with a higher age than 50 years tend to make <=50K, perhaps because of their inability to work or due to retirement. These observations line up with the distributions in Figure 1.1 and 1.2, where the sub-distribution of people with an income level >50K is shifted to the right. Thus, we can conclude that as the age of an individual tends to 50 years old, and their years of education received increase, then their probability of making >50K increases as well.

This result makes sense because generally, people who attend or graduate from university get access to higher paying jobs than people with only a high school education. Additionally, as people age, they progress in their careers which is usually done through promotion at their jobs or receiving more competitive salaries at other companies. All of this culminates in a higher yearly income.

This result also aligns with current census data. According to census data from Canada in 2016, women with a bachelor's degree earned significantly more than women with other education levels, earning 40% more than women with only an associate's degree, and 60% more than women with only a high school level education ("Census in Brief").

The impact of our findings can have real-world applications. For instance, since we found that most people with a university-level education made >50K, then a government can choose to increase funding to the education sector (or universities specifically) to promote economic growth ("Financing Education"). Conversely, it was found that most people who are older than 50 tend to make less as they age. From this, governments and companies can decide to make adjustments to pension or retirement plans to support the older generation, among other things.

An extension to this project would be to analyze some of the predictors themselves, particularly the ones which we did not factor into our classifier because they were not numeric for simplicity's sake. For instance, we could analyze race and sex to view the relationship between race and gender and see if there is any wealth disparity that is visible in the data. However, in order to do this, we would likely have to gather more data from underrepresented groups, as the current data set that we have has more data collected from white males than any other group. Barring that, for example, if it was found that most people with a high education_num were of a certain race and sex, then governing bodies may want to take action to reduce this inequality and increase the representation of minorities at higher education institutions.
